com.opengamma.strata.market.key

Class QuoteKey

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.opengamma.strata.market.key.QuoteKey
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    MarketDataKey<Double>, ObservableKey, SimpleMarketDataKey<Double>, StandardIdentifiable, Serializable, Bean, ImmutableBean

    public final class QuoteKey
extends Object
implements ObservableKey, ImmutableBean, Serializable
    Market data key identifying the current and historical values of a market identifier.

    A quote key identifies a piece of data in an external data provider.

    Where possible, applications should use higher level keys, instead of this class. Higher level market data keys allow the system to associate the market data with metadata when applying scenario definitions. If quote keys are used directly, the system has no way to perturb the market data using higher level rules that rely on metadata.

    The StandardId in a quote key is typically the key from an underlying data provider (e.g. Bloomberg or Reuters). However the field name is a generic name which is mapped to the field name in the underlying provider by the market data system.

    The reason for this difference is the different sources of the key and field name data. The key is typically taken from an object which is provided to any calculations, for example a security linked to the trade. The calculation rarely has to make up an key for an object it doesn't have access to.

    In contrast, calculations will often have to reference field names that aren't part their arguments. For example, if a calculation requires the last closing price of a security, it could take the key from the security, but it needs a way to specify the field name containing the last closing price.

    If the field name were specific to the market data provider, the calculation would have to be aware of the source of its market data. However, if it uses a generic field name from FieldNames the market data source can change without affecting the calculation.

    See Also:
    FieldName, Serialized Form

      • toMarketDataId

        public QuoteId toMarketDataId(MarketDataFeed marketDataFeed)
        Description copied from interface: ObservableKey
        Converts this key to the matching identifier.

        Market data keys identify a piece of market data in the context of a single calculation, whereas market data identifiers are a globally unique identifier for an item of data.

        For example, a calculation has access to a single USD discounting curve, but the system can contain multiple curve groups, each with a USD discounting curve. For cases such as curves there is a mapping step to transform keys to IDs, controlled by the market data rules.

        The market data key for an observable item of market data contains enough information to uniquely identify the market data in the global set of data. Therefore there is no mapping step required for observable data and the market data ID can be directly derived from the market data key.

        Specified by:

        Specified by:
